The '''National Survey of Sexual Attitudes and Lifestyles''' ('''NATSAL''') is the name given to a series of face-to-face surveys of people in the [[United Kingdom]] regarding their sexual behaviour and patterns. The three rounds of interviews completed to date are NATSAL-1 (1990–91) and NATSAL-2 (2000-01) and NATSAL-3 (2010–12).<ref>[http://www.natcen.ac.uk/study/natsal Natsal: The National Survey of Sexual Attitudes and Lifestyles], National Centre for Survey Research.</ref> The results are widely used in research and policy making. NATSAL's principal investigator is [[Anne Mandall Johnson|Anne Johnson]], a professor at [[University College London|University College, London]],<ref>{{cite web |title=Survey examines changes in sexual behaviour and attitudes in Britain |url=http://www.wellcome.ac.uk/News/Media-office/Press-releases/2013/Press-releases/WTP054816.htm |website=www.wellcome.ac.uk |accessdate=2015-10-14}}</ref> and co-leader [[Kaye Wellings]], a professor at the [[London School of Hygiene & Tropical Medicine]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Lane|first=Richard|date=2013-11-30|title=Kaye Wellings: pioneering figure in sexual health|url=http://www.thelancet.com/journals/lancet/article/PIIS0140-6736(13)62346-6/fulltext|journal=The Lancet|language=English|volume=382|issue=9907|doi=10.1016/S0140-6736(13)62346-6|issn=0140-6736}}</ref>

The Natsal-3 survey revealed, among other things, that British people are having sex less often than they did 20 years ago.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cambridge professor's in-depth analysis of sex survey reveals couples' secrets beneath the sheets |url=http://www.cambridge-news.co.uk/Cambridge-professor-s-depth-sex-survey-reveals/story-26249577-detail/story.html |accessdate=30 March 2015 |publisher=Cambridge News |date=29 March 2015}}</ref>

